      "writtenOn": "2015-07-16T11:28:07Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "nit: please add a \\n at the end of line.\n\nnit2: On Windows, snprintf() does *not* zero-terminate the buffer in case of overflow [1]. Yes, this is insane, but it means that, if the result is negative, you should either add the zero manually, as in:\n\n    executable[PATH_MAX - 1] \u003d \u0027\\0\u0027;\n    fprintf(stderr, \"....%s\\n\", executable);\n\nOr use length-based format specifier:\n\n    fprintf(stderr, \"...%.*s\\n\", PATH_MAX, executable);\n\n[1] https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/aa298594(v\u003dvs.60).aspx",
      "revId": "c33eb3b79e8e6f9ec28c2de735ffbd4becbf25c1",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
